{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
False equivalence arguments, between the right to discriminate and the right to be free from discrimination, are also unavailing because the true clash of rights in a case like 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Masterpiece Cakeshop
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 is between the civil right to have the state prevent private parties from discriminating against you (represented by the public accommodations laws) and the liberty of avoiding the state\rquote s coercing you to perform labor that you wish to avoid, which may amount to compelled speech (represented by the First Amendment). The Christian baker does not want \u8220\'3ftolerance\u8221\'3f for his ability to discriminate; he is instead asserting his civil liberty against state coercion in the form of compelled speech.
}
