{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Under the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment, the state may not target particular groups in ways that undermine their dignity and autonomy, but, without state action, private individuals are allowed to express ideas that offend others to the very core.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EARBG_1}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EARBG_1}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
This argument becomes more complicated when discussing requiring professors to create diversity statements. Affirming the equal dignity of every student, regardless of status characteristics, is a critical part of a professor\rquote s job and creates an environment where students can best learn. Professors who actively and explicitly make statements to students reflecting racial- or gender-based animus are doing their students a disservice, and the school can rightly intervene. 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
That said, professors who simply hold different views on affirmative action, or speak out against perhaps over-compensatory diversity measures, should not be deemed to be undermining the dignity of their students. In an academic setting, students need to tolerate views that upset them, or even disturb them to their core, especially from other students, and perhaps even from professors.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
}
